article.headline: Sting maintain second place in East
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- As teammates and fans waited anxiously as
referees huddled around a video monitor, Dawn Staley had no doubt
her winning shot was good.

Staley's bank shot at the buzzer gave the Charlotte Sting a
69-68 comeback victory Saturday over the Connecticut Sun.

Andrea Stinson's runner bounced hard off the backboard and into
the hands of Staley, who lofted a 5-footer high off the glass as
time expired. The officiating crew replayed the videotape of her
shot several times before determining Staley got her shot off
before the horn went off.

"I knew my shot was good because I saw the light on the
backboard go off after the ball was out of my hand," Staley said.
"When I was going up for the rebound it seemed like the ball came
off perfectly -- it didn't hit the rim or anything."

Stinson scored 19 points, Shalonda Enis added 14, and Staley had
11 as the Sting (16-12) rallied from a 15-point deficit to maintain
sole possession of second place in the Eastern Conference.

Nykesha Sales tied a career-high with 29 points, and Katie
Douglas added 10 for the Sun (14-14), losers of two straight.

Douglas made a 3-pointer with 26.4 seconds left to put
Connecticut ahead before Staley's heroics.

"It was a game we should've won," Connecticut coach Mike
Thibault said. "It shouldn't have come down to that last play. We
played good defense, but gave up a second-chance shot. It's a tough
way to lose a game."

The Sun led 51-37 on Taj McWilliams-Franklin's 3-pointer with
13:07 left, but Charlotte chipped away at Connecticut's lead.

The Sting went on a 10-2 run, capped by Enis' free throw with
2:49 left, to grab a 62-60 lead. It was Charlotte's first advantage
since they led 9-8.

The Sun dominated the inside in the first half, grabbing 14 of
the game's first 16 rebounds.

McWilliams-Franklin's free throw with 9:39 left capped a 14-0
run to give Connecticut a 26-11 lead. Sales' 3-pointer in the final
minute put the Sun on top 40-30 at halftime.

Sales went 7-of-12 from the field and made 13 of 16 free throws.

"Our game plan was to play tough defense, and I think we did a
great job the majority of the game," Sales said, but Charlotte
"hit some really tough shots."
